title: For Sale:  WWII Japanese Ariska Rifle  PRICE DROP
postcontent:
PLEASE NO OUT OF STATE OFFERS, unless you come to get them.  Shipping is a hassel and cost too much.
This WWII Japanese Ariska rifle is a Type 99 manufactured by Nagoya Arsenal between 1923-1945.  Its stamped with the chrysanthemum mark, that is the symbol of the Japanese Emperor.
During the period, if the weapon was surrendered the chrysanthemum symbol was partially ground off as a face saving gesture.  If the chrysanthemum symbol is intact then the rifle was captured as this one shows.
The rfle is in excellent condition for being from that period of time and circumstances, it is however missing the front wooden handguard.  More pictures are available for those that are interested.

title: For Sale:  Mosin Nagant Scope Mount SCAM!
postcontent:
The following listed ad has been copied from a dealer's Armslist Ad and is in violation of US Copyright laws.

The ad claims that the mount is the new cross-bolt mount, but the  photos show it to be the old two screw mount which has been discontinued because they strip out the threads in the mount and the mount comes loose and unstable.

ASK THE SELLER TO VERIFY HIS MOUNT HAS THE NEWER CROSS-BOLT MOUNT BEFORE YOU BUY IT.

Photos of the newer cross-bolt mount are shown below for comparison. Also. . . note that the newer cross-bolt mount is shorter than the older long mount which interferes with proper mounting of his scope.
===========================================

For Sale/Trade: Mosin Nagant M91/30 Scope/Rail/Rings/Accessories
Seller: 	Private Party 	Listed In: 	Accessories
Location: 	Springs Ranch, Colorado Springs, Colorado [Map]

I have a new scope, picatinny rail, rings and accessories to include bayonet for an M92/30 Mosin Nagant and similar models. This scope kit was designed to mount to the existing rear sight easily with no gunsmithing at all. You can return your MN back to original at any time. Includes everything in pictures including allen keys and instructions for mounting picatinny rail. Accessories include Russian Mosin-Nagant Model 1891 socket bayonet - Second Pattern - designed for the Mosin-Nagant Infantry Rifle. These are considered Communist Russian (post-1918), Oiler, 2 slings, 2 double ammo pouches an tool kit.


Includes: 2-7x32MM Variable Power Wide Angle Scout Scope with Duplex Reticle, “No Gunsmith” Cross Bolt Picatinny Rail Scope Mount, and Low Profile Scope Rings.

Scope Specifications:
+ Manufactured by Aim Sports Inc
+ Magnification: Wide Angle 2~7 Variable Power
+ Duplex Reticle
+ Objective Lens: 32mm
+ One Inch Tube
+ Weight: 9.0 Ounces
+ Length: 10 3/8 inches
+ Extended Eye Relief
+ Matte Black Finish
+ Windage/Elevation: 1 Click = 1/4" @100 Yards
+ Multi-Coated Lenses
+ Bright Optics
+ Sharp Focusing
+ Eye Piece Focus Lock Ring
+ Nitrogen Filled - Fog and Water Proof
+ Shock Proof – Heavy Duty Recoil Design
+ Protective Lens Caps Included

Mount Specifications:
+ New Third Generation Scout Scope Mount.
+ Fits Mosin Nagant 7.62x54R Rifles and Carbines.
+ For Russian, Hungarian and Polish Carbine Models 38 and 44, Finnish Models M27, M28 and Chinese Model 53 with the 2 3/8" Long 1000 Meter Graduated Rear Sight
+ For Rifle Models 91, 91/30, 91/38 and 91/59 with the 3 3/8" Long 2000 Meter Graduated Rear Site
+ Will Fit Finland 7.62x53R M91/30 but not other models. Some Finnish M91/30 rifles have a high handguard and may require higher rings
+ Easy Installation - "No Gunsmithing" Mount Replaces Rear Sight and Bolts into the Rear Sight Base (Note: Some minor fitting may be required)
+ Use with Weaver Style Rings
+ For Extended Eye Relief (EER) Scopes, Hologram and Red Dot Sights
+ Hardened Aluminum Mount with Multiple Picatinny Rail Slots
+ Mounting Hardware and Installation Instructions Included
+ Restore Rifle to Original Configuration by Removing Mount and Reinstalling the Rear Sight

** This new scope mount has been designed to provide lower "visual alignment" mounting for scout scopes. Alloy steel cross bolt mounting to the rear sight base with a locking nut provides a secure installation and insures that this mount will not shoot loose.

The easily installed, "no gunsmithing" mount replaces the rear sight leaf. (Detailed installation instructions are included with the mount). Simply remove the rear sight leaf and leaf spring, then insert and bolt in the scout mount. Attach the included Weaver style rings to the Picatinny mount and install the extended eye relief (EER) scout scope. You can restore the rifle to its original configuration by unbolting the scope and mount and reinstalling the rear sight.

Some Mosin Nagant scope mounts were designed with two short bolts that attach through the side “ears” of the rear sight base and thread into the scope mount. With extended shooting these bolts strip out the threads in the aluminum scope mount and the mount comes loose. Our mount has been threaded completely through and is fitted with a full length threaded alloy steel cross bolt and retaining nut that securely attaches the scope mount to the rear sight base.

Ring Specifications:
+ Strong Lightweight Aluminum
+ Non-Slip Mounting
+ Matte Black Finish

title: For Sale:  Star Model B 9mm Luger
postcontent:
The Star Model B was made in Spain and is chambered in 9mm Luger. The proof markings and serial number indicate that this pistol was made in 1945 but was not issued to a military force as it does not have a military proof mark. The round count is unknown but I have personally fired approx 50 rounds through it with no problems. The pistol is very accurate and the barrel is in good shape, no pitting and the rifling is strong. There is quite a bit of wear to the bluing as well as some scratches and dings but no rust. It comes with one 8 round magazine. Asking $300 but negotiable on the price. 

History:
The "Second Model" added several, mostly external, features to make the pistol look and handle more like the Colt 1911A1. The frame was changed to provide an arched backstrap and a larger safety as well as more rugged and higher-visibility sights.

About the M59/66A1:
The Zastava 7.62 mm M59/66A1 gas-operated self-loading rifle closely resembles the Russian Federation Simonov SKS rifle. Initially copies of the original SKS-45 were made in Yugoslavia and given the designation M59, later a permanently attached grenade-launcher spigot and grenade launcher sight were added and the new weapon designated the M59/66. The final model was the M59/66A1.
